<P>16. The total amount of the occupancy costs is $12,803.28. The parties agreed that The Hive would pay $75,000 Canadian in total for rent and occupancy costs. The rent from The Hive was payable in U.S. dollars and difference between the rent and the $75,000 Canadian, $8,125, was applied to occupancy expenses.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>2008</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Moongate</UNDER></TI>
<P>17. The Appellant owns a property located at XXXXXXXXXX (&ldquo;Moongate&rdquo;).</P>
<P>18. Moongate is a waterfront property located near Cook's Bay.</P>
<P>19. The Appellant entered into a verbal agreement to lease Moongate to Mandrake Properties Inc. (&ldquo;Mandrake Properties&rdquo;) in 2004.</P>
<P>20. Mandrake Properties' business is to manage and lease properties.</P>
<P>21. The Appellant is the sole shareholder of Mandrake Properties.</P>
<P>22. Mandrake Properties entered into a sublease agreement with The Hive in 2004. The Hive used the property to entertain its employees, clients and guests.</P>
<P>23. Mandrake Properties reported the income from Moongate in its tax return.</P>
<P>24. The Hive required modifications to Moongate to entertain its guests and for a proposed marketing venture. The Hive requested that a pathway be modified to allow for easier access to a nearby beach.</P>
<P>25. Mandrake Properties agreed to make the modifications requested by The Hive. The parties agreed to share the costs of renovating Moongate.</P>
<P>26. The renovations to Moongate were completed in 2007. The Appellant provided payment to vendors for the renovations on behalf of Mandrake Properties in 2007 with the expectation that he would be repaid.</P>
<P>27. Mandrake Properties paid for The Hive's share of the costs, $42, 910.45 including Goods and Services Taxes (&ldquo;GST&rdquo;), on the condition that it would be reimbursed. The Appellant issued an invoice dated May 21, 2008 to The Hive for $42, 910.45 for the costs of the modifications.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Reimbursements Invoiced on February 1, 2008</UNDER></TI>
<P>28. The Appellant, acting as an agent for Mandrake Properties, travelled to Florida in January 2008 to provide marketing assistance to The Hive.</P>
<P>29. The Appellant provided a number of marketing suggestions that were accepted by The Hive.</P>
<P>30. The Hive did not pay for the Appellant's time, but agreed to reimburse Mandrake Properties for expenses related to the Appellant's travel to Florida. The Hive also agreed to reimburse the Appellant for damages to Sloans Curve.</P>
<P>31. The Appellant, acting as agent for Mandrake Properties, issued an invoice dated February 1, 2008 to The Hive for reimbursement for his travel expenses and the damage to Sloans Curve. The invoice was for the reimbursement of the amounts of $14,970.97, $23,934.27 and $7,101.85.</P>
<P>32. The total amount reimbursed during this period by The Hive to Mandrake Properties was $43,816.26 or $46,007.09 including GST.</P>
<P>33. The Hive reimbursed Mandrake Properties by paying the invoiced amount to the Appellant.</P>
<P>34. The Appellant paid Mandrake Properties by cheques for the expenses in the amount of $14,970.97, $23,934.27 and $7,101.85 on January 31, 2008, January 31, 2008 and January 24, 2008, respectively.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Reimbursements for Travel Expenses and Sloans Curve Expenses Invoiced Separately</UNDER></TI>
<P>35. The Appellant and Ms. Peerenboom travelled several times to Florida to supervise the repair and refurnishing of Sloans Curve. The unit and the furniture inside of it were damaged during The Hive's tenancy.</P>
<P>36. The Hive agreed to reimburse the Appellant and Ms. Peerenboom's travelling costs as well as the costs related to the repair of Sloans Curve.</P>
<P>37. The Appellant invoiced The Hive for $31,542.85, $24,691.55, and $27,385.00 on February 1, 2008, May 28, 2008 and May 30, 2008, respectively.</P>
<P>38. The amount invoiced on February 1, 2008 for $31,542.85 was reimbursement for travel expenses as well as to replace burned lawn furniture, repair a broken barbeque, and restock food supplies.</P>
<P>39. The amount invoiced on May 28, 2008 for $24,691.55 included expenses other than travel costs. The Appellant invoiced The Hive for $24,691.55 in error and the amount of the invoice should have been approximately $11,000.</P>
<P>40. The amount invoiced on May 30, 2008 for $27,385 was for the purchase and installation of shutters. Sloans Curve had a set of five hurricane shutters for its windows. The damage to Sloans Curve during The Hive's tenancy included damage to two of the five shutters. The Appellant replaced all of the shutters, so that shutters were uniform throughout the property, at a cost of $27,385.</P>
<P>41. The rules of Sloans Curve's condominium building require that the shutters be in working order and uniform in color</P>
<P>42. The total amount billed to The Hive on the separate invoices dated February 1, 2008, May 28, 2008 and May 30, 2008 was $83,619.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Audit of The Hive</UNDER></TI>
<P>43. The Minister audited The Hive and found that the reimbursements to Appellant, Mandrake Properties and Ms. Peerenboom were recorded as payments to a consultant.</P>
<P>44. The Hive erroneously reported the reimbursements it paid to the Appellant as payments to a consultant.</P>
<P>45. The Minister issued T4A slips to the Appellant for amounts recorded as consultant fees by The Hive.</P>
<P>46. On May 28, 2010, the Minister issued Notices of Reassessment for the Appellant's 2007 and 2008 taxation year to include the reimbursements in the Appellant's income.</P>
